    print('-'*120)

    plt.legend(loc='lower left', frameon=False)

Illustrate the insights based on EDA¶

  • Age is right skewed. There are very few customers of age 75+ for obvious reasons. There is only one Exited customer older then 75. She is 84, and there are only 2 cutomers of age 84. We will change age of all these customers 75+ to 76 to avoid model triggering on age 84
  • All customers with credit score below 405 exited. We will change credit score below 410 to exactly 410 to avoid model overfitting on left tail of Credit score distribution
  • 95% of customers have 1 or 2 products. Only 0.5% os customers have 4 products. All customers with 4 products exited, but there are very few of them. We will merge customers with 3 and 4 products to avoid model overfitting on customers with 4 products
  • Behaviour of customers varies significantly depending on number of products. Customers with 2 products are most loyal, customers with 3 and 4 products are least loyal; customers with 1 product are somwhere in between. NumOfProducts looks more like categorical variable now.
  • Females exit more often then males
  • Customers from Germany exit more often then customers from Spain and France
  • Active members exit less frequently
  • While mean customer age is ~39, mean age of exiting customers is ~45
  • While mean balance is ~75K, mean balance of exiting customers is ~90-95K
  • There is no strong linear correlation between numerical features

Model building¶

  • Build Neural Network

Define some helper functions¶

In [185]:
import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf
import random as python_random

def random_seed(seed = 123):
  
  # The below is necessary for starting Numpy generated random numbers
  # in a well-defined initial state.
  np.random.seed(seed)

  # The below is necessary for starting core Python generated random numbers
  # in a well-defined state.
  python_random.seed(seed)

  # The below set_seed() will make random number generation
  # in the TensorFlow backend have a well-defined initial state.
  # For further details, see:
  # https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/random/set_seed
  tf.random.set_seed(seed)

Function below builds neural network

  • Caller should provide number of hidden layers, number of nodes per hidden layer, optimizer, batch size, number of epochs and multiplier for default learning rate (since default LR are different for different optimizers)
  • In the beginning of the proc we call random_seed() to reproduce the same results between runs
  • We use dropouts to help prevent overfitting. Dropout rate is also provided by the caller
  • We use training set to train NN and validation set for performance validation during training. Test set is used for evaluation of model performance when training is done
In [186]:
def buildNeuralNetwork(n_layers, n_nodes, activation, loss_f, optimizer, 
                       lr_mult, batch, epochs, X, y, n_inputs, do_rate,
                       callbacks, verbose):
  random_seed()
  model = Sequential()
  #input layer
  model.add(ks.Input(shape = (n_inputs,)))
  #alternative input layer
  #model.add(Dense(n_nodes, input_shape=(n_inputs, ), kernel_initializer='he_normal', activation='relu'))
  #hidden layers  
  n_nodes_layer = n_nodes * 1.5
  for i in range(0, n_layers):
    n_nodes_layer /= 1.5    
    model.add(Dense(n_nodes_layer, activation=activation))
    if do_rate  > 0:
      model.add(Dropout(do_rate))
  #output layer
  model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

  sample_weight = np.ones(shape=(len(y),))
  sample_weight[y == 1] = 4

  opt = optimizer
  
  old_lr = optimizer.get_config()['learning_rate']
  new_lr = old_lr * lr_mult
  opt.learning_rate.assign(new_lr)
  print("Change LR from {} to {}".format(old_lr, opt.learning_rate))

  metrics = [
    ks.metrics.FalseNegatives(name="fn"),
    ks.metrics.FalsePositives(name="fp"),
    ks.metrics.TrueNegatives(name="tn"),
    ks.metrics.TruePositives(name="tp"),
    ks.metrics.Precision(name="precision"),
    ks.metrics.Recall(name="recall"),  
    ks.metrics.AUC(name='AUC'),
    ks.metrics.PrecisionAtRecall(0.7, name='PaR'),
 ]

  model.compile(optimizer=opt,
              loss=loss_f,
              metrics=metrics,
              )
  #history = model.fit(X, y, epochs=epochs, batch_size=batch, verbose=verbose,  
  #          sample_weight=sample_weight, validation_split=0.25, 
  #          callbacks = callbacks)
  history = model.fit(X, y, epochs=epochs, batch_size=batch, verbose=verbose, 
            sample_weight=sample_weight, validation_data=(X_val_np, y_val_np),
            callbacks = callbacks)

  ##restore learning rate
  opt.learning_rate.assign(old_lr)
  return model, history

calc_custom_metric calculates custom metric for model performance estimation. It will be explained below

In [187]:
recall_weight = 2
## Custom metric: see explanation below

def calc_custom_metric(y, y_pred):  
  tn, fp, fn, tp = skmetrics.confusion_matrix(y, y_pred).ravel()
  tpr = tp / (tp + fn)
  fpr = fp / (fp + tn)
  custom = (1 + recall_weight * tpr - fpr) / (recall_weight + 1) 
  return custom  

def get_model_metrics (model, x, y, threshold, out):
  y_pred = model.predict(x)
  y_pred = y_pred[:,0]
  step_f = lambda x : 0 if x < threshold else 1
  y_pred = np.array([step_f(xi) for xi in y_pred])


  recall, precision, f1, cm, custom = \
           skmetrics.recall_score(y, y_pred), \
           skmetrics.precision_score(y, y_pred),\
           skmetrics.f1_score(y, y_pred),\
           skmetrics.confusion_matrix(y, y_pred), \
           calc_custom_metric(y, y_pred)
  if (out):
    print ("Recall: {0:.2}, Precision: {1:.2}, f1:{2:.2}, custom metric:{3:.2}:".format(recall, precision, f1, custom))
  
  return recall, precision, f1, cm, custom

Functions in the below cell are used to calculate optimal threshold using custom metric

In [188]:
def find_nearest(array, value):
    array = np.asarray(array)
    idx = (np.abs(array - value)).argmin()
    return idx

def find_best_threshold(y, y_pred):
  fpr, tpr, thresholds = skmetrics.roc_curve(y, y_pred)

  optimal_idx = np.argmax((recall_weight * tpr - fpr))
  return thresholds[optimal_idx]

In [189]:
def make_confusion_matrix(cm,labels=[1, 0]):
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - Loyal","Actual - Exited"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - Loyal','Predicted - Exited']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

def plot_history(history,  keys):
  for key in keys:
    plt.plot(history.history[key])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_'+key])
    plt.ylabel(key)
    plt.xlabel('epoch')
    plt.legend(['train','test'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()
In [191]:
def plot_roc_auc(model, X, y, best_th=-1):
  y_pred=model.predict(X)[:,0]
  fpr_keras, tpr_keras, thresholds_keras = skmetrics.roc_curve(y, y_pred)
  auc_keras = skmetrics.auc(fpr_keras, tpr_keras)
  plt.figure(1)
  plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
  plt.plot(fpr_keras, tpr_keras, label='Keras (area = {:.3f})'.format(auc_keras))
  plt.xlabel('False positive rate')
  plt.ylabel('True positive rate')
  plt.title('ROC curve')
  if (best_th >= 0) :
    best_idx = find_nearest(thresholds_keras, best_th)
    best_x = fpr_keras[best_idx]
    best_y = tpr_keras[best_idx]
    plt.plot(best_x, best_y, 'ro', label='Best score')
  plt.legend(loc='best')
  plt.show()
  plt.show()

def plot_precision_recall(model, X, y, best_th):
  y_pred=model.predict(X)[:,0]
  pr_keras, rc_keras, thresholds_keras = skmetrics.precision_recall_curve(y, y_pred)
  plt.figure(1)
  plt.plot(pr_keras, rc_keras, label='Precision vs Recall')
  plt.xlabel('Precision')
  plt.ylabel('Recall')
  plt.title('Precision-Recall curve')
  if (best_th >= 0) :
    best_idx = find_nearest(thresholds_keras, best_th)
    best_x = pr_keras[best_idx]
    best_y = rc_keras[best_idx]
    plt.plot(best_x, best_y, 'ro', label='Best score')
  plt.legend(loc='best')
  plt.show()
  plt.show()

<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7efd7d8df410>

Threshold can be changed to make model performance better. Before finding the optimal threshold we should decide what metric we are going to use

Loosing a customer has a big impact on bank and we should identify as many of exiting customers as possible, which means True Positive Rate a.k.a. Recall should be maximized. But NN can maximize recall by simply identify all the customers as Exiting. To prevent that we should penalize our metric for every loyal customer identified as exiting. \begin{equation} metric= w_{recall} * TPR - FPR \end{equation} $w_{recall}$ is a weight of an Exiting customer compared to the weight of a loyal customer. For example, if identifying of exiting customer is twice as important as identifying a loyal customer, then $w_{recall} = 2$. This metric is in range of [-1, $w_{recall} - 1$]. In order to place it in [0,1] range we should modify metric as follows: \begin{equation} metric= \frac{(1 + w_{recall} * TPR - FPR)}{1+w_{recall}} \end{equation} This metric is calculated by finction calc_custom_metric. Custom Test data score for the original NN is 0.74

Learning rate adjustment¶

As mentioned earlier, loss function demonstrates oscilations which is a sign of leaning rate being too high. We can try to start reducing learning rate after certain epoch to supress oscilations

In [226]:
from tensorflow.math import  exp

def lr_scheduler(epoch, lr):
  if epoch < 10:
    return lr
  elif epoch == 10:
    return lr * 0.5
  else:
    return lr * exp(-0.05)
In [227]:
lr_cb = ks.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(lr_scheduler)
callbacks = [lr_cb]

  • Threshold optimizatios doesn't add much value to our custom metric. It just rundomly increse recall and decrese precision or the othe way around. Since the behaviour of this technique is unpredictable for this type of problem, we won't consider models with modified threshold
  • Neural network with learning rate adjustment and early stop has a high recall. It also stops at the minimum of the loss function for validation set and has a very small loss function oscilation magnitude at the end of the curve, which is a sign of good fit. We would recommend this model

Further improvement model can include:

  • Hyperparameter tuning for loss functions, number of nodes/layers, activation functios, dropout ratio
  • Different weight initialization techniques
  • Seeding random number generators with different values to find better a local minimum
  • Adopt global otimization technique like Similated annealing to find a global minimum

Conclusion and key takeaways¶

  • NN performance is sensetive to different parametrs like number of layers and nodes, activation and loss functios
  • Divergence of training and validataion loss functions can be fixed by adding layers and nodes. For fine tuning add nodes, for coarse tuning add layers
  • NN training results are sensetive to initial weigh, which means it's a global optimization problem
  • Callbacks like Learning rate scheduling and early stop help to improve NN training proces
